'''Kari''', in [[shakuhachi]] music, is both a property of a note and a technique. To play a note kari means to play it with raised [[pitch (music)|pitch]], relative to playing the note [[Meri (note)|meri]]. In addition to sharpening the pitch, playing a note kari also modifies the tone color or [[timbre]] of a note.
The usual technique to play a note kari is to raise the chin, increasing the angle and distance between the [[embouchure]] and [[utaguchi]] (blowing edge).
== References == * {{cite web | last = Kakizakai | first = Kaoru | authorlink = Kakizakai Kaoru | title = Another Benefit to Kari Blowing | url = http://www.kotodama.net/shakuhachi/2000/dec2k.html | accessdate = 2006-11-29}} * {{cite web | last = James | first = Phil Nyokai | authorlink = Phil Nyokai James | title = Shakuhachi Tips: Meri-Kari | url = http://nyokai.com/tips/index.php?n=Tips.Meri-Kari | accessdate = 2006-11-29}}
