'''Reflectins''' are a family of [[intrinsically disordered proteins]] evolved by a certain number of [[cephalopods]] including [[Euprymna scolopes]] and [[Doryteuthis opalescens]] to produce [[Iridescence|iridescent]] camouflage and signaling. The recently identified protein family is enriched in [[Aromaticity|aromatic]] and [[sulphur]]-containing [[amino acid]]s, and is utilized by certain [[cephalopod]]s to refract incident light in their environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=DeMartini |first1=Daniel G. |last2=Izumi |first2=Michi |last3=Weaver |first3=Aaron T. |last4=Pandolfi |first4=Erica |last5=Morse |first5=Daniel E. |title=Structures, Organization, and Function of Reflectin Proteins in Dynamically Tunable Reflective Cells |journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry |volume=290 |issue=24 |pages=15238–49 |year=2015 |pmid=25918159 |doi=10.1074/jbc.M115.638254 |pmc=4463464}}</ref> It is possible that reflectins are [[beta barrel]] type proteins.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Weiss |first1=Jamie L. |last2=Evans |first2=Nicholas A. |last3=Ahmed |first3=Tanweer |last4=Wrigley |first4=Jonathan D.J. |last5=Khan |first5=Shukria |last6=Wright |first6=Charles |last7=Keen |first7=Jeffrey N. |last8=Holzenburg |first8=Andreas |last9=Findlay |first9=John B.C. |title=Methionine-rich repeat proteins: a family of membrane-associated proteins which contain unusual repeat regions |journal=Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (BBA) - Biomembranes |volume=1668 |issue=2 |pages=164–74 |year=2005 |pmid=15737327 |doi=10.1016/j.bbamem.2004.11.014 }}</ref> It is present in the iridophores and leucophores of cephalopods.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Guan|first=Zhe|last2=Cai|first2=Tai|date=2017|title=Origin of the reflectin gene and hierarchical assembly of its protein|url=|journal=Current Biology|volume=27|pages=|via=}}</ref> There is evidence that the reflectin gene appeared in cephalopods due to a horizontal gene transfer with the marine bioluminescent bacterium, ''Aliivibrio fischeri''.<ref name=":0" />

